2 HOUSE BILL 812
1 (4) “Electronic health network” has the meaning stated in § 4–302.3 of this
2 subtitle.
3 (5) “Nursing home” has the meaning stated in § 19–1401 of this article.
4 (b) (1) If a nursing home contracts with or uses an electronic health network
5 or electronic medical record vendor, the nursing home may direct the electronic health
6 network or electronic medical record vendor to release patient medical records or electronic
7 health care transactions held by the electronic health network or electronic medical record
8 vendor to a business associate of the nursing home.
9 (2) An electronic health network or electronic medical record vendor
10 releasing patient medical records or electronic health care transactions under paragraph
11 (1) of this subsection:
12 (i) Shall release the patient medical records or electronic health
13 care transactions in an electronic format that conforms to the specifications of the Office of
14 the National Coordinator for Health Information Technology or another form required by
15 the State–designated health information exchange;
16 (ii) Shall make the patient medical records or electronic health care
17 transactions available on a regular basis and release the information in a timely manner
18 to support patient care and monitoring; and
19 (iii) May not restrict, limit, or charge a fee for the release of the
20 patient medical records or electronic health care transactions.
21 (C) THE OFFICE OF THE ATTORNEY GENERAL MAY ENFORCE THIS
22 SECTION.
23 (D) (1) ANY PERSON, INCLUDING A PERSON IDENTIFIED UNDER
24 SUBSECTION (B)(1) OF THIS SECTION, MAY BRING AN ACTION FOR DAMAGES,
25 INJUNCTIVE RELIEF, OR BOTH AND FOR ATTORNEY’S FEES AGAINST ANY PERSON IN
26 VIOLATION OF THIS SECTION.
27 (2) A PERSON MAY BRING AN ACTION UNDER THIS SUBSECTION
28 WHETHER THE PERSON INTERACTED DIRECTLY OR INDIRECTLY WITH THE PERSON
29 IN VIOLATION OF THIS SECTION.
30 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
31 October 1, 2025.

